<span id="freeTextContainer13672365821654036303">A backward, reactionary, nationalistic prose piece disguised as an essay on aesthetics, which engages in strange speculation and musing that is not at all well supported. But it gets better towards the end when its cantankerousness and hyperbole get amusing, and it does ultimately manage to express a mournful nostalgia for a dying aesthetic, even if that aesthetic is more of a personal aesthetic than the author admits, rather than being an expression of national character.<br/><br/>P.S.<br/><br/>The aesthetic can b</span>
  <span id="freeText13672365821654036303" style="display:none">A backward, reactionary, nationalistic prose piece disguised as an essay on aesthetics, which engages in strange speculation and musing that is not at all well supported. But it gets better towards the end when its cantankerousness and hyperbole get amusing, and it does ultimately manage to express a mournful nostalgia for a dying aesthetic, even if that aesthetic is more of a personal aesthetic than the author admits, rather than being an expression of national character.<br /><br />P.S.<br /><br />The aesthetic can be summarized thus: "Turn the lights down, it's too bright in here, especially for people with yellow skin."</span>
