  <span id="freeText14516390350927667064" style="display:none">After reading about the concept of Wabi-Sabi in Leonard Koren`s book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42190.Wabi_Sabi_for_Artists__Designers__Poets___Philosophers" title="Wabi-Sabi for Artists, Designers, Poets &amp; Philosophers by Leonard Koren" rel="nofollow noopener">Wabi-Sabi: for Artists, Designers, Poets &amp; Philosophers</a> it was only natural to continue with this essay. Again this was very enriching, but this one was a lot more poetic and captivating. The descriptions are vivid and are beautifully written, which is not simple when writing about Japanese aesthetics (though the essence of this concept is actually the beauty that is in the simple and fleeting things). </span>
