        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1335270132" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6681750126126937745">The Japanese aesthetics of the bygone days -- the book was originally published in 1933. (Don&apos;t expect to see this by visiting Japan now.) Quite unique. Perhaps most interesting for the American/European readers is the way he appreciates women&apos;s beauty. <br/><br/>Tanizaki was not just any Japanese writer. He was well versed with the Japanese classics. His modern Japanese translation of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7042.The_Tale_of_Genji' title='The Tale of Genji by Murasaki Shikibu' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Tale of Genji</a> was a standard for a long time, and I think it still is one of the best. NOT coincidentally, Edward Sei</span>
  <span id="freeText6681750126126937745" style="display:none">The Japanese aesthetics of the bygone days -- the book was originally published in 1933. (Don't expect to see this by visiting Japan now.) Quite unique. Perhaps most interesting for the American/European readers is the way he appreciates women's beauty. <br /><br />Tanizaki was not just any Japanese writer. He was well versed with the Japanese classics. His modern Japanese translation of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7042.The_Tale_of_Genji" title="The Tale of Genji by Murasaki Shikibu" rel="nofollow noopener">The Tale of Genji</a> was a standard for a long time, and I think it still is one of the best. NOT coincidentally, Edward Seidensticker, who translated Genji to English, translated many of Tanizaki's works, including this. <br /><br />I'd recommend this to those who are super serious about Japanese literature. </span>
