au. The present volume is an unabridged English translation of the 13th French edition of that historic manifesto, in which Le Corbusier expounded his technical and aesthetic theories, views on industry, economics, relation of form to function, the &quot;mass-production spirit,&quot; and much else. A principal prophet of the &quot;modern&quot; movement in architecture, and a near-legendary figure of the &quot;International School,&quot; he designed some of the twentieth century\'s most memorable buildings: Chapel at Ronchamp; Swiss dormitory at the Cit√© Universitaire, Paris; Unit√© d\'Habitation, Marseilles; and many more.\n\nLe Corbusier brought great passion and intelligence to these essays, which present his ideas in a concise, pithy style, studded with epigrammatic, often provocative, observations: &quot;American engineers overwhelm with their calculations our expiring architecture.&quot; &quot;Architecture is stifled by custom. It is the only profession in which progress is not considered necessary.&quot; &quot;A cathedral is not very beautiful . . .&quot; and &quot;Rome is the damnation of the half-educated. To send architectural students to Rome is to cripple them for life.&quot;\n\nProfusely illustrated with over 200 line drawings and photographs of his own works and other structures he considered important, Towards a New Architecture is indispensable reading for architects, city planners, and cultural historians‚Äïbut will intrigue anyone fascinated by the wide-ranging ideas, unvarnished opinions, and innovative theories of one of this century\'s master builders.<\/span>\n  <a data-text-id=\"1676261926448134862\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent(\$(this));; return false;\">...more<\/a>\n\n    <\/div>\n\n      <div class=\'wtrButtonContainer wtrSignedOut\' id=\'15_book_70134\'>\n<div class=\'wtrUp wtrLeft\'>\n<form action=\"/shelf/add_to_shelf\" accept-charset=\"UTF-8\" method=\"post\"><input name=\"utf8\" type=\"hidden\" value=\"&#x2713;\" /><input type=\"